stuck up on top of his head like a paint brush,\par
"Well, I dunno," he said. "But come in my office and I'll tell you what happened, anyway."\par
"What do the police think?" Frank asked him, as jhey followed.\par
"Didn't ask the police," Slow Mo said. "Jake, the chief-he's my brother-in-law-ain't solved a case in thirty years. That's why I called your pop."\par
The old man crossed the floor of the musty-smell~ ing garage and entered a two-by-four room. It was Stacked high with empty oil cans and old tires.\par
On the wall hung a faded calendar dating back years. It was the only calendar in the place. Slow Mo had kept it, he said, because he liked the fisherman pictured on it.\par
"Haven't you a calendar for this year?" Frank queried.\par
Slow Mo gave a sheepish smile. "Never thought of that," he said.\par
"Where's your office?" Joe asked with a wink at Frank.\par
"Why, gol hang it, boy," Slow Mo said, "I can see right now you're not the detective your father is. This is the office. He'd of knowed that right off."\par
"Sorry," Joe replied, keeping a straight face.\par
"Set down here," the proprietor offered, motioning toward a couple of kegs.\par
The brothers seated themselves as Slow Mo un\'bb\par
