folded his story. Most of it they already knew. At one point Joe interrupted to ask for a description of the couple who had left the car.\par
Slow Mo looked blank for a moment, then said, "Why, they're kinda ordinary-lookin' folks, middlin' height, dressed like reg'lar people-"\par
Joe shook his head. Slow Mo's description would apply to a million other strangers!\par
"Where did the couple go after they left their car?" Frank asked.\par
"Took a train from here," Slow Mo replied. "Station's right over there," he said, pointing.\par
Pleasantville's one pride was being the terminal of a railroad spur. It served several towns along its route to Bayport.\par
"What's the engine number of the car?" Frank quizzed.\par
"Why, I dunno," Slow Mo answered. "Guess I should 'a' looked at it. Never thought of that."\par
He led the Hardys to the rear of the garage, where a black sedan stood in a corner.\par
Frank threw up the hood of the automobile and glanced at the engine.\par
"Got a flashlight?" he asked Slow Mo.\par
When the proprietor handed him one, Frank scanned the motor.\par
"Just as I thought!" he exclaimed. "The engine number has been filed off."\par
The Mysterious Car 3\par
"What would anybody do that for?" Slow Mo asked, running his fingers through his bristle top.\par
"To conceal the identity of the car," Frank explained. "This," he added, "is a case for the local police chief, whether you like him or not."\par
Slow Mo telephoned him. Soon afterward a short, fat man puffed into the garage.\par
"Hello, Jake," Slow Mo said. "These are the Hardy boys. Sons of Fenton Hardy, the detective."\par
"What have they done?" Jake asked. "Want 'em arrested?"\par
"No," Frank said, laughing. "We'd like you to arrest the person who filed the number off the engine of this car." He pointed to the mysterious black sedan.\par
"Besides, the guy that left it here owes me two months' rent," put in Slow Mo.\par
An eager look spread over Police Chief Jake's face. His nose grew red and his eyes narrowed as he wiped his shiny bald head with a bright bandanna handkerchief.\par
"I'll arrest him, all right. Where is he?"\par
"That's what we'd like to find out," Frank said. "Slow Mo said he left here two months ago."\par
"Got a head start, didn't he?" Jake reasoned. "But I'll get him."\par
Jake blew his nose three times, like an elephant trumpeting for his mate, then looked inside the car.\par
6 The Sign of the Crooked Arrow\par
"Stand back now, boys," he said, "while I look for some clues."\par
Joe smothered a laugh when the chief pulled a big magnifying glass from his back pocket. The officer seemed interested only in what lay on the surface of the car. After a five-minute study he said gravely:\par
"I think this car was stolen." Then he added with authority, "I'll send out a seven-state alarm." With that the chief puffed out of the building.\par
"Guess that does it," Slow Mo said with a shrug.\par
"Does what?" asked Joe.\par
"Solves the case," Slow Mo replied. "Just like he solves all the cases in Pleasantville; not at all."\par
Frank spoke up. "If that's true, suppose Joe and I look for some clues."\par
"Sure, go ahead," the garage owner said.\par
Frank started a systematic study of the car's upholstery, while his brother removed the mats from the front and rear floors. Presently, from inside the front compartment, which otherwise was empty, Joe drew out a narrow leather strap. It was worn at one end.\par
"Looks like part of an old strap from a wrist watch," he commented, showing it to Frank. "Wonder why anyone would save it."\par
"It may be a valuable clue," his brother said.\par
He himself continued to probe the cushions. He\par
The Mysterious Car 7\par
pulled out the back seat and ran his hand behind the upholstery. His reward was a hairpin and a ten-cent piece. Then suddenly his fingers tightened around a strange object. Tugging carefully, the boy pulled out an ornamental piece of jewelry.\par
"A tie clasp," Frank announced, holding the object in his palm.\par
"It's an arrow, but it's crooked," Joe observed.\par
Slow Mo peered closely at the slightly S-shaped arrow tie clasp. "Probably got bent," he said, "when somebody sat on it."\par
"I don't think so," Frank replied. "It looks to me as if it were made that way."\par
Pocketing the piece of strap and the tie clasp, the Hardys said good-bye to Slow Mo and left the garage. Joe got behind the wheel for the trip home and Frank slid in beside him. Just as Joe was about to press the starter button, a rough-looking man turned in from the road and walked into the garage.\par
"I wonder who that guy is?" Joe asked. "Looks like a prize fighter."\par
Frank and Joe waited a moment. They heard the men's voices from inside, arguing loudly.\par
"We'd better see what's the matter," Frank said. "Sounds as if Slow Mo's in trouble."\par
The brothers got out of their car and started inside. As they did, the stranger snarled at Slow Moi\par
8 The Sign of the Crooked Arrow\par
"All right, I didn't leave it! And I don't care if the license plates are gone. I'm taking this car!"\par
With that he gave Slow Mo a wallop. The elderly garage owner staggered backward and fell.\par
His head struck the concrete floor with a resounding crack and he sprawled unconscious.\par
