Now Joe was running after a man who gave every evidence of being involved in some crooked dealing. The boy was only a few yards behind him as he raced up the wooden steps of the old Pleasantville station, three at a time. At that moment a train was pulling out.\par
With a lunge, the man grasped the handrail on the last coach, teetered precariously a moment, then pulled himself aboard. By this time the train was moving fast.\par
Joe missed his man by inches. In disgust, he returned to the garage and told Frank, who was bathing Slow Mo's head with cold water.\par
"How is he?" Joe asked.\par
"He's coming to," Frank replied.\par
As the boys watched, Slow Mo's eyelids fluttered and opened.\par
"Wh-where am I?" he asked in a daze.\par
"In your office," Frank replied. "Take it easy."\par
"I remember now," the man said. "Big guy hii me. Where'd he go? Did he get the car?"\par
When Frank told him the mysterious stranger had escaped, but without the car, Slow Mo breathed a sigh of relief.\par
"I'm glad he got away. He might have hurt you boys. I wouldn't want anything to happen to Fenton Hardy's sons on my account."\par
Assured that Slow Mo was well enoueh to be left\par
