the boys drove off to the police station to tell Chief Jake what had happened.\par
"I'll send out a seven-state alarm," the officer puffed. "Nobody can come to Pleasantville and sock my brother-in-law!"\par
A few minutes later Frank and Joe left the police station and headed back to Bayport.\par
"I don't like the looks of this, Joe," Frank said, frowning.\par
His brother agreed. "What's your guess? Think it really is that man's car?"\par
"No. Probably trying to collect it for the fellow who left it."\par
"Then why the big rush to get out of the garage? I'll bet he was trying to steal the car!"\par
"What I want to know," Frank declared, "is who took the license plates and obliterated the engine number."\par
All the way back to Bayport the brothers tried vainly to figure out what was back of the mystery. "Perhaps Dad can," Joe said as they reached home and entered the Hardy driveway.\par
The boys hurried into their father's study and found him seated in a red leather chair poring over a dossier of criminal records. When his sons entered, the detective laid the papers aside.\par
"Hello, boys," he said. "How did you make out at Slow Mo's?"\par
