Joe turned a chair around and straddled it, while Frank sat on the edge of his father's desk. Mr. Hardy knew something unusual was in the air.\par
"Well, tell me," he urged. "Have you two run into something hot?"\par
"Dad," Frank said seriously, "there's something crooked about that abandoned car out at Slow Mo's place."\par
Fenton Hardy raised his eyebrows and sat forward in his chair. Frank told his story, then showed his father the worn watch strap and the crooked arrow tie clasp.\par
"What do you make of it, Dad?" Joe asked impatiently.\par
"Boys," replied Mr Hardy, "I believe you've dug up some clues which may tie in with a case I'm working on; a very baffling case."\par
"What's that?" Frank put in, amazed.\par
"You've been reading about the wave of robberies in and about Bayport, haven't you?"\par
The boys nodded as the detective went on. "The Businessmen's Association has engaged me to apprehend the criminals. They think the police are a bit slow," he said, smiling.\par
"The \i Bayport Times \i0 believes an out-of-town gang is committing the robberies," Frank said.\par
"Yes, I know, but I don't agree with the \i Times," \i0 replied his father. "I'll admit it does look as if a\par
